[2026-04-12T12:04:09.446136+00:00] OSINT Dorks Used: ['site:arxiv.org filetype:pdf "**Structural Alpha Thesis: Eigenspectrum Decay Acceleration vs. Correlation Entropy Divergence (ED-CE Regime)**\n\n**Target:** Sharpe > 1.20 via structural exploitation of the information geometry embedded in the empirical spectral measure of the cross-sectional correlation matrix.\n\n### Mathematical Logic (step-by-step)\n\n**Step 1 – Spectral Representation**\nLet $\\mathbf{R}_t \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N\\times N}$ be the rolling Pearson correlation matrix computed on log-returns over a fixed-length window $\\tau=252$. Perform spectral decomposition:\n$$\n\\mathbf{R}_t = \\mathbf{V}_t \\boldsymbol{\\Lambda}_t \\mathbf{V}_t^\\top, \\quad \\boldsymbol{\\Lambda}_t = \\text{diag}(\\lambda_1(t) \\geq \\lambda_2(t) \\geq \\dots \\geq \\lambda_N(t)), \\quad \\sum_{i=1}^N \\lambda_i(t) = N.\n$$\nDefine the normalized empirical spectral measure:\n$$\np_i(t) = \\frac{\\lambda_i(t)}{N}, \\quad i=1,\\dots,N, \\quad \\sum p_i(t)=1.\n$$\n\n**Step 2 – Dual Spectral Observables**\n- **Eigenspectrum Decay Exponent ($\\alpha_t$)**: Estimate the decay rate of the ordered eigenvalues via weighted least-squares on the log-log scale for $i=2,\\dots,k_{\\text{max}}$ (where $k_{\\text{max}} \\approx N/4$ to avoid noise floor):\n  $$\n  \\log\\lambda_i(t) \\approx c(t) - \\alpha_t \\log(i) + \\epsilon_i(t).\n  $$\n  $\\alpha_t > 0$ large ⇒ rapid decay ⇒ strong market factor dominance (low-dimensional effective structure).\n\n- **Correlation Entropy ($S_t$)**: Shannon entropy of the normalized spectrum:\n  $$\n  S_t = -\\sum_{i=1}^N p_i(t)\\log p_i(t).\n  $$\n  Theoretical bounds: $0 < S_t \\leq \\log N$. Low $S_t$ confirms concentration in top eigenvectors; high $S_t$ indicates eigenvalue democratization (random-matrix-like regime).\n\n**Step 3 – Information Divergence Signal**\nConstruct the composite regime variable that captures the *joint* dynamics of decay acceleration and entropy collapse:\n$$\nZ_t = \\underbrace{(\\alpha_t - \\bar{\\alpha}_{\\tau})}_{\\text{decay acceleration}} \\times \\underbrace{(\\bar{S}_{\\tau} - S_t)}_{\\text{entropy contraction}},\n$$\nwhere $\\bar{\\alpha}_{\\tau}$ and $\\bar{S}_{\\tau}$ are exponentially weighted moving averages ($\\lambda=0.94$). \n\nThe economic interpretation is precise: positive $Z_t$ identifies periods when the market is *both* rapidly concentrating explanatory power into fewer principal components *and* destroying correlation entropy. These are precisely the transitions from diversified noise regimes into coherent, low-dimensional flows — periods that historically exhibit strong subsequent mean-reversion in relative value across the eigenvector basis.\n\n**Step 4 – Eigenvector-Relative Positioning**\nAt each $t$ where $Z_t > \\theta$ (threshold calibrated to top quintile of historical distribution):\n- Extract the first $K=3$ eigenvectors $\\mathbf{v}_1(t),\\dots,\\mathbf{v}_K(t)$.\n- Project all assets onto the orthogonal complement of the dominant subspace to obtain residual returns:\n  $$\n  \\tilde{\\mathbf{r}}_t = (\\mathbf{I} - \\mathbf{V}_K(t)\\mathbf{V}_K(t)^\\top)\\mathbf{r}_t.\n  $$\n- Rank assets by their residual standardized deviation from the subspace projection.\n- Form a dollar-neutral portfolio that is *long the most positive residual eigenvectors* and *short the most negative residual eigenvectors*, sized inversely to their $L^2$ loading on the dominant subspace (i.e., assets most "misaligned" with current coherent flow receive largest risk allocation).\n\n**Step 5 – Dynamic Risk Scaling**\nScale portfolio notional by a monotonic function of signal strength:\n$$\n\\text{Notional}_t = \\text{Base} \\times \\frac{Z_t}{\\sigma_Z} \\times \\exp(-\\gamma \\cdot \\text{PC1}(t)),\n$$\nwhere $\\text{PC1}(t)=\\lambda_1(t)/N$ is the market mode fraction (exponential decay term prevents leverage during extreme concentration events). Volatility target is enforced via ex-ante 21-day realized covariance of the residual portfolio.\n\n**Step 6 – Exit and Regime Neutrality**\nPositions are held until either (a) $Z_t$ crosses below zero, or (b) 10-day entropy begins increasing while decay flattens (spectral reversal), whichever occurs first. No overnight gaps; all logic is Markovian in the spectral state.\n\n### Theoretical Justification for Sharpe > 1.20\nThe strategy is long the *rate of change of spectral coherence*. Because equity cross-sections exhibit persistent eigenvalue repulsion after coherence shocks (Marchenko-Pastur repulsion dynamics), the subsequent renormalization of relative values across the orthogonal complement produces repeatable alpha with low correlation to both momentum and value factors. The dual filter ($Z_t$) removes false positives that plague pure entropy or pure eigenvalue-ratio signals, explaining the expected jump from prior baseline Sharpe ~0.84 to >1.20 in walk-forward testing.\n\nThis is a pure structural bet on the market’s latent dimensionality dynamics rather than on directional returns or factor loadings."']
